
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Influence of Organization Structure on Role Conflict and Ambiguity for Three Occupational Groupings
AU  - Morris, James H.
AU  - Steers, Richard M.
AU  - Koch, James L.
Y1  - 1979/03/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255478
DO  - 10.5465/255478
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 58
EP  - 71
VL  - 22
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The impact of organization structure on perceptions of role conflict and ambiguity was examined within a multivariate framework and found to explain substantial portions of variation in both role perceptions. These structural influences were generally supported across three occupational groupings: professional employees (n = 55); secretarial/clerical employees (n = 127); and blue-collar employees (n = 70) within one public organization. Minor differences were noted between occupational groupings with respect to which structural properties were more influential in determining role perceptions.
AB  - The impact of organization structure on perceptions of role conflict and ambiguity was examined within a multivariate framework and found to explain substantial portions of variation in both role perceptions. These structural influences were generally supported across three occupational groupings: professional employees (n = 55); secretarial/clerical employees (n = 127); and blue-collar employees (n = 70) within one public organization. Minor differences were noted between occupational groupings with respect to which structural properties were more influential in determining role perceptions.
