TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Nature of the Task as a Moderator of the Relationship Between Extrinsic Feedback and Employee Responses
AU  - Kim, Jay S.
AU  - Schuler, Randall S.
Y1  - 1979/03/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255488
DO  - 10.5465/255488
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 157
EP  - 162
VL  - 22
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article presents information on a study which suggests a possible reconciliation of the conflicting findings on the relationship between extrinsic feedback and employee responses by incorporating the nature of task as a moderator variable. It infers that the conflicting findings on the relationship between extrinsic feedback and employee response may be caused by a failure to incorporate the nature of a given task. It also states that the use of extrinsic feedback is contingent upon the nature of the employee's task when considering employee satisfaction and internal motivation.
AB  - This article presents information on a study which suggests a possible reconciliation of the conflicting findings on the relationship between extrinsic feedback and employee responses by incorporating the nature of task as a moderator variable. It infers that the conflicting findings on the relationship between extrinsic feedback and employee response may be caused by a failure to incorporate the nature of a given task. It also states that the use of extrinsic feedback is contingent upon the nature of the employee's task when considering employee satisfaction and internal motivation.
